WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.200
Hi, I'm Kelly from RStudio, and this video is a demo of programmatic deployment of a

00:00:07.200 --> 00:00:16.260
Shiny application to RStudio Connect using Jenkins and GitHub Webhooks.

00:00:16.260 --> 00:00:22.160
This deployment pipeline leverages new RStudio Connect server APIs for content management

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:27.120
that have just become available in RStudio Connect 1.7.0.

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:32.040
This is the deployment pipeline that I've built using GitHub and Jenkins to move from

00:00:32.040 --> 00:00:37.880
the RStudio IDE all the way to RStudio Connect.

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:43.360
So here's the application that I'm interested in programmatically deploying to Connect.

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:46.959
I'll show it to you here in the RStudio IDE.

00:00:46.959 --> 00:00:51.939
You can interact with it here locally, and I'll also show it to you as already deployed

00:00:51.939 --> 00:00:53.680
to my Connect server.

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:55.279
So here it is on the Connect server.

00:00:55.439 --> 00:01:01.360
You can see here that it's just a basic histogram Shiny application, and I've changed the color

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:05.360
of the histogram to red.

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:12.040
Now I'll pull up my IDE again and say I'm interested in changing the color from red

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:15.739
back to something more subtle like blue.

00:01:15.739 --> 00:01:20.080
So in order to do that, I'm going to use a git branching strategy.

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:27.639
I'm checking out a new branch, which I'm calling new branch, and now I'll be able to

00:01:27.639 --> 00:01:33.519
commit all of my code changes to this branch before pushing up to GitHub.

00:01:33.519 --> 00:01:39.699
So here I'm just changing the color from red to dark blue, and then I'm going to save that

00:01:39.699 --> 00:01:43.199
and test the app locally.

00:01:43.199 --> 00:01:44.199
Here it is locally.

00:01:44.199 --> 00:01:46.559
I like the color.

00:01:46.559 --> 00:01:53.160
So now I'll push that change up to my GitHub.

00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:59.400
So to do that, I will add this change and then write a little commit message here about

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:09.880
what happened to the code, say I changed the color, and then I'll push my branch up to GitHub.

00:02:17.559 --> 00:02:24.559
So now if I go over to my GitHub, my repository here, you'll see I have a new branch that

00:02:24.559 --> 00:02:28.279
I can then open a pull request on.

00:02:28.279 --> 00:02:34.800
So here I'm just opening a pull request for this change so that I can merge the branch

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:42.240
into master and push that change information over to Jenkins.

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:46.320
I have a pull request ready to go, and at this point, I could request a review from

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:51.240
somebody else on my team, but while I'm here, I'll show you in the settings that I have

00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:56.800
a webhook already pre-set up to talk to Jenkins from my GitHub repo.

00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:01.720
If you want to see more information about how to set that up, check out the blog in

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:02.720
the description below.

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:10.800
But now I'm going to go ahead and merge my PR into master, and that will kick off my

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:13.399
Jenkins job.

00:03:13.399 --> 00:03:14.399
This is my Jenkins server.

00:03:14.399 --> 00:03:21.160
I'm going to sign in again real quick here.

00:03:21.160 --> 00:03:28.559
You can see that I have this Freestyle Jenkins project that's deploying my code changes over

00:03:28.559 --> 00:03:30.639
to RStudio Connect.

00:03:30.639 --> 00:03:35.440
Again, for more information on how to set up this Freestyle project, check out the blog

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:40.440
in the description below.

00:03:40.600 --> 00:03:49.199
I go over to Connect, refresh, and I can see I have a blue histogram instead of a red one.

00:03:49.199 --> 00:03:54.360
Go back and show you real quick some of the things that you can explore in Jenkins based

00:03:54.360 --> 00:03:55.360
on each build.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:04:00.520
If you're interested in looking at what happened, you can always go into your console output

00:04:00.520 --> 00:04:03.720
in Jenkins and investigate each job.

00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:05.639
You'll see here that we had a success.

